review_blob: Nice Pils.  Light yellow color with a huge white head.  German version has an almost floral taste (like Budvar) but the U.S. version is a bit off.  This ratings for the German version.
The import version has a malty backbone, with just the right amount of hops - a standard, standby lager.  However, it isnot usually worth the U.S. price - its the German 1 club special.
Slightly better than the average Hefeweizen - thick consistency but drinkable.  Great malt balance - not too citrus-y or banana-y.
Not a terrible NA.  Nice straw color, heavy carbonation.  Hops are clearly present.  Always seems to taste a bit "skunky" - have bought it two or three times now with the same result.

Golden, decent head that leaves a little bit of lacing.  Just a maltier version of the ol Pils - nothing awful, just nothing outstanding.  In comparison to the other Bindings, like a slightly hoppier lager (also pretty unspectacular).
Exactly what youd expect a lager to be.  However, theres nothing that really pushes this beer over the edge, so that it approaches greatness.
Slightly maltier version of the Pils.  Goes down easily.  True "fluessiges Brot."
Berliner Weisse with the green Schuss included.  Looks different than if the Schuss has just been added, but the Waldmeister (woodruff) syrup really tones down the Weissbier.  Great summer beer.
beer_name: Berliner Kindl Weisse Mit Schu Waldmeister

review_blob: Sickly sweet pink color, sickly sweet taste - it tastes more "pink" than "raspberry."  So little alcohol, itll freeze in the back of your refrigerator.  Go for the typical Weisse with a real Schuss of raspberry syrup, dont get this prepackaged stuff!
beer_name: Berliner Kindl Weisse Mit Schu Himbeere

review_blob: The original Berliner Weisse.  Light yellow, bitter.  Head sticks around for a while.
Dry and sharp - hops have taken over.  Not as bitter as most of the other Pilsner beers created in the area.  Head dissipates pretty quickly.
Nice and bready, with a citrus/banana back - well balanced.  You cant see your hand through the glass!  Goes down nice and smooth.
Really fizzy, goes down easily.  However, it lacks a lot of the awesome yeasty flavor from the standard Hefeweizen.
Thin, bitter, bright yellow.  Metallic aftertaste. Not too bad with a Doener.
People seem to love or hate this one.  Well-crafted pils, but a little on the bitter side.
You cant see your hand through the glass!  Nice fluffy head.  Citrusy, tangy flavor - I prefer my Hefeweizens to have more of a banana taste.
Not sweet, but not too bitter either - *the* Munich Helles.  Bready.  Straw-colored, fluffy head, carbonation that doesnt take over.
Practically black.  Smells sweet, but tastes smoky, alcohol clearly present, which takes over all the other flavors in the beer.
The way a Doppelbock should be.  Orange-brown in color, bready, perfect balance of sweetness (definite taste of fig and honey) and dryness, no alcoholic aftertaste.
Pretty standard Hefeweizen.  Very tart and sour (reminded me of a Berliner Weisse!).  Lots of carbonation.
Almost the color of cola.  Starts off sweet, ends up tasting of coffee and chocolate, a bit bitter.
Dark amber color, cream-colored head that lingers and leaves a lot of lacing.  Tastes of dried fruit and honey, chocolate - sweet and malty.  Alcohol is well hidden.
Pretty disappointed.  Thin, smoky flavor.  Alcohol taste is too strong and astringent on the palate.  I love Doppelbocks, and this one was disappointing.
Looked almost like a cola in the glass.  Malty, overly sweet, with a medicinal aftertaste.
Tastes and goes down like a standard lager, just a bit more hoppy .  Head sticks around for a bit, but I wouldnt call it creamy.
Dark amber in color, almost no head.  Sweet in the mouth, dry, slightly bitter finish.  Strangely nowhere near as hoppy as their normal Rye Pale Ale.
Beautiful dark red color, starts off smooth and malty on the palate but finishes sharp and dry.
Dark amber color, nice cream-colored head, tastes of clove and fig.  Sweet but not too sweet.
Orange-brown color, very carbonated.  Sweet and dark, mild taste of alcohol.  Would drink it again, but Fin du Monde is a stronger offering.
Unibroues weakest offering, in my opinion.  Not much apple to it.  Watery consistency, light yellow color, almost no head.  Reminded me of a watery, boozy juice Schorle.
One of my current favorites.  Smells and tastes sweet - yeasty and slightly citrusy but not overwhelming.  Alcohol content well-hidden.  Goes down easily.
Nice dark brown color with big, cream-colored head.  Lots of malt, well-hidden hops (they can surprise you), lots of dried fruit flavors.  Almost like a less intense version of Abt 12.
Looks beautiful - amber color, just the right amount of carbonation.  Head dissipated quickly.  Much more bitter than most Tripels, and the most disappointing beer Ive had from St. Bernard.
Dark color, thick head that lingers and leaves a lot of lacing.  Sweet flavor - cherry, fig, raisin - but not too sweet.  High ABV more noticeable as the beer slowly warms.
Great, especially on tap.  Dark and sweet, not really any bitterness. Bit of a dark cherry flavor.  Weak carbonation.

In the bottle: almost unbearably bitter aftertaste.

On tap: yeah, tastes like a standard pils.  

A lot of carbonation, nice head, nice lacing. Not bad if you can find it on tap at a U.S. German restaurant.
Very malty, bready.  Goes down easily.  Tastes more like a lager than a pils.  Also tastes significantly different on tap versus in the bottle.  Sweeter on tap, more bitter in the bottle.
Looks beautiful, but the carbonations a bit heavy and its also pretty bitter, especially compared to other Pils produced in the area.
Nice Hefeweizen and one of the brewerys better offerings.  More of a banana base than a citrus base.  Goes down easily.
Goes down smoothy but am otherwise unsure what to think. Quality varies from bottle to bottle.  Sometimes its hoppy, sometimes its malty.  Theres a reason why Munich Helles is much better known.
Not the best offering from Schwabenbraeu.  Just average for a Maerzen.  Medium brown color, high carbonation, slightly bitter.
Overall a weak offering from Schwabenbraeu.  Thin, bready, not as sweet as most Schwarzbiere.
Pretty standard German pils.  Had the U.S. version, imported by Binding.  Tastes more like the German Binding than a Dortmunder-style beer.  Crisp, dry, more malty than hoppy.
A bit darker than the Broadside and appears about the same.  The bitterness is a bit overwhelming when consumed alone; would be good with some sort of roast.
Not much of a scent. Thin head, not really any lacing.  Truly a bitter, but the maltiness makes it more drinkable.
Smells great, like theres chocolate and coffee malt in there.  Color of black coffee, but a bit thicker, with a thick white foamy head.
Have had this a number of times.  Weak raspberry flavor, but it enhances the lager a little bit.  Very dry finish.  Not the best beer ever, but good on a hot summer day.

Almost syrupy, tastes artificially sugary.  Not bad, just not beery.  Have had this (in Luxembourg) and also La Becasse (in France), which, according to Ratebeer, is supposed to be the same thing - the consistency of La Becasse is more watery, and tastes more like cough syrup.  Would say that Belle-Vue is okay but would recommend staying away from La Becasse.

This is actually one of my favorite Hefeweizen beers.  Sweet but not too sweet, tart but not too tart, more banana-y than citrus-y (what I prefer in a Hefeweizen), very filling.  Not so bad in a bottle but preferable on tap.
I was expecting much more from this Kriek.  It tasted artificially sweet as well as too tart. I was expecting much more from Lindemans, and prefer their Peche and Framboise.
